<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Morphological description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
The frustule is cylindrical, valves approximately flat, 21.4-27.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diameter, in the middle of a valve 5 processes are located, 4-5 marginal fultoportulae in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, situated on the valve margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. SEM (A, B and E-H) and LM (C, D) images of species found in the transitional zone at Mykolaiv city: A-D Pleurosira laevis A, C valve views with arrows shown the ocelli B girdle view E Conticribra weissflogii, valve view with arrows shown central and marginal fultoportulae F Thalassiosira incerta, valve view with arrow shown central fultoportulae G Thalassiosira faurii, valve view H Minidiscus proschkinae, valve view with arrow in the centre shown central fultoportula, and closer to the edge - rimoportula. Scale bars: 10 μm (C-G); 30 μm (A); 50 μm (B); 3 μm (H)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.178.64426.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545736" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">4F</figureCitation>
). The rimoportula is short-necked with an elongated, compressed narrow lip usually perpendicular to the margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
The species was recorded as planktonic in water bodies of different types, typical for eutrophic/hypertrophic and highly saprobic marine, brackish, and fresh waters. It is euryhaline and eurythermal, in addition to being known as an alkaliphilic taxon (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995082916020139" author="Okhapkin, AG" journalOrPublisher="Inland Water Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="126 - 134" refId="B97" refString="Okhapkin, AG, Genkal, SI, Vodeneeva, EL, Sharagina, EN, Bondarev, OO, 2016. To ecology and morphology of Thalassiosira incerta Makarova (Bacillariophyta). Inland Water Biology 9 (2): 126 - 134, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995082916020139" title="To ecology and morphology of Thalassiosira incerta Makarova (Bacillariophyta)." url="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995082916020139" volume="9" year="2016">Okhapkin et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Mediophyceae" family="Thalassiosiraceae" genus="Thalassiosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Thalassiosira incerta" order="Thalassiosirales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="incerta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Thalassiosira incerta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was named an invasive taxon for Russia (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kaštovský">Kastovsky</normalizedToken>
2010; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1134/S2075111714020052" author="Korneva, LG" journalOrPublisher="Russian Journal of Biological Invasions" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="65 - 81" refId="B73" refString="Korneva, LG, 2014. Invasions of alien species of planktonic microalgae into the fresh waters of Holarctic. Russian Journal of Biological Invasions 5 (2): 65 - 81, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1134/S2075111714020052" title="Invasions of alien species of planktonic microalgae into the fresh waters of Holarctic." url="https://doi.org/10.1134/S2075111714020052" volume="5" year="2014">Korneva 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Mediophyceae" family="Thalassiosiraceae" genus="Thalassiosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Thalassiosira incerta" order="Thalassiosirales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="incerta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Thalassiosira incerta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recorded near Mykolaiv city in the Southern Bug River (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Species composition of centric diatoms at the investigated sites near Mykolaiv city in the Southern Bug River in the year 2017 (2013 added for station 2)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" tableUuid="DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677">1</tableCitation>
). For Ukrainian territory, there are few records from reservoirs of the Dnipro River and some estuaries of the Black Sea and coastal waters near Crimea (
<bibRefCitation author="Tsarenko, PM" journalOrPublisher="Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B127" refString="Tsarenko, PM, Wasser, SP, Nevo, E, 2009. Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A.R.A. Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" title="Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A. R. A." year="2009">Tsarenko et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
This taxon is quite cosmopolitan, and distributed in the Boreal of Europe (Great Britain, Russia, Ukraine), Asia (Azerbaijan), North America (Canada, USA), Africa (Egypt); Aral, Black and Caspian Seas (
<bibRefCitation author="Sims, PA" journalOrPublisher="Biopress Ltd., Bristol" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B112" refString="Sims, PA, 1996. An atlas of British diatoms arranged by B. Hartley based on illustrations by H.G. Barber and J.R. Carter. Biopress Ltd., Bristol" title="An atlas of British diatoms arranged by B. Hartley based on illustrations by H. G. Barber and J. R. Carter." year="1996">Sims 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kuo, YC" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B79" refString="Kuo, YC, Guo, YC, 2003. Flora algarum marinarum sinicarum. Tomus V. Bacillariophyta No. I. Centricae. Science Press, Beijing" title="Flora algarum marinarum sinicarum. Tomus V. Bacillariophyta No. I. Centricae." year="2003">Kuo and Guo 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995082916020139" author="Okhapkin, AG" journalOrPublisher="Inland Water Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="126 - 134" refId="B97" refString="Okhapkin, AG, Genkal, SI, Vodeneeva, EL, Sharagina, EN, Bondarev, OO, 2016. To ecology and morphology of Thalassiosira incerta Makarova (Bacillariophyta). Inland Water Biology 9 (2): 126 - 134, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995082916020139" title="To ecology and morphology of Thalassiosira incerta Makarova (Bacillariophyta)." url="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995082916020139" volume="9" year="2016">Okhapkin et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Genkal, SI" journalOrPublisher="Filigran, Yaroslavl" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B45" refString="Genkal, SI, Kulikovskiy, MS, Kuznetsova, IV, 2020. Modern freshwater centric diatom algae in Russia [Sovremennye presnovodnye centricheskie diatomovye vodorosli Rossii]. Filigran, Yaroslavl" title="Modern freshwater centric diatom algae in Russia [Sovremennye presnovodnye centricheskie diatomovye vodorosli Rossii]." year="2020">Genkal et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
